# Wide Events (Canonical Log Lines)

Source: [loggingsucks.com](https://loggingsucks.com/)

## Mental model

Log **what happened to this request**, not what your code is doing. Emit **one wide event per request per service** at the end of the lifecycle — not 10+ scattered lines.

Structured JSON is table stakes. Wide events are a philosophy: high **cardinality** (user IDs, request IDs) and high **dimensionality** (many queryable fields).

## Build once, emit once

Initialize context at request start; enrich in handlers; emit in `finally`:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — scattered, unqueryable
console.log("Payment failed");
logger.info(`Processing user ${userId}`);

// ✅ GOOD — one authoritative record
event.user = { id: user.id, subscription: user.subscription };
event.payment = { provider: "stripe", latency_ms: 1089, attempt: 3 };
event.error = { type: "PaymentError", code: "card_declined", retriable: false };
logger.info(event); // emit once in finally
```

Include: `request_id`, `trace_id`, service/version/deployment, HTTP method/path/status, `duration_ms`, user + business context (cart, feature flags), and structured errors.

## Querying, not grepping

Fields must be consistent key names (`user_id`, not `user-123` in prose). Design logs for the 2am search: "checkout failures for premium users with new_checkout_flow enabled."

## OpenTelemetry

OTel is a delivery mechanism. It does not decide what to capture — instrument deliberately with business context. Ideally, wide events are enriched trace spans.

## Sampling at scale

Use **tail sampling** after the request completes:

- Always keep: errors (5xx, exceptions), slow requests (above p99), VIP/flagged users
- Random-sample the rest (1–5%)
